{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_alastor_ver02/data/sn78003992/00340580953/1948070901/0030.xml":{"full_text":"May Ask City CIO'\nCouncil's Help In\n\u201cCold Strike\u201d\nAkron CIO Council may be asked at\nits meeting Monday night to give its\nsupport to the \u201ccold strike-\u2019 of the\nAssociation of Communication Equip\nf ment Workers, CIO, in its \u2018\u201ccold\nstrike\u201d against the Western Electric\nCompany, a subsidiary of the multi\nmillion dollar American Telephone\nand Telegraph Co.\nThe appeal, if it is made, will be\npresented by G. B. Phillips, Akron\ndistrict representative of the associa\ntion.\nThe \u201ccold strike,\u201d which has taken\nthe form of simply passing out pam\nphlets and handbills stating the work\ners* side of the dispute, may blossom\ninto a regular strike at any moment,\ndue, according to Mr. Phillips, to the\ncompany\u2019s utter refusal to grant a\nwage increase to its employes over\nthe entire nation.\nThe company maintains that be\ncause it reduced its prices five per\ncent it cannot grant a- wage increase.\nProfits of the company amounted to\nover \u00a554,000,000 last year.\nWages being paid by the company\nat present are much below those in\nthe rubber, steel and various other\nindustries in which pay increases re\ncently have been granted. Many work\ners receive less than $1.00 per hour,\nas compared with an average of over\n$1.50 per hour paid in the rubber in\ndustry.\nThe company also is insisting that\nunion officers, in order to retain their\npositions with the company, must\nwork at least half of the time, thus\ngreatly curtailing their time available\nfor union activities. They also insist\u2019\nthat workers be sick for 14 days be\nfore receiving sick benefits, and they\ndecline to guarantee jobs of workers\n-when they return'after being drafted\nby the armed forces.\nLate last week Akron members of\nthe association demonstrated in front\nof the Ohio Bell Telephone Company\nBuilding, but no effort was made to\nkeep employes from entering the\nbuilding. The present. contract ex\npired July 1st.\nThunder can be heard more than\n20 miles away from the flash, but in\nDecember, 1953, a dynamite explosion\nset off on the Arctic island of Nova\nZcmbia was hearl in Berlin 2,000\nmiles away.\nWhole Future of Labor\nHanging in Balance\nAt Philadelphia\n(Continued from Page One)\nE. Dewey regardless of whom the\nDemocratic Party nominated?\u201d\nSome answer that question with an j\nemphatic, \u201cNO!\u201d William Green,\npresident of the American Federation\nof Labor, already has come out in op\nposition to the Republican candidate.\nVarious other Labor leaders apparent\nly are holding their fire until the\nDemocratic convention has acted.\nThose already lined up against\nDewey point to the fact that two\nyears ago the 'Republican Party con\nsidered its political victory a \u201cman\ndate\u201d from the American people to\n\u201ccrack down\u201d on Organized Labor,\nwith the result that the Taft-Hartley\nLaw was enacted.\nThey argue now that if the Re\npublican Dewey is victorious at the\npolls in November, that it will again\nbe considered a \"mandate,\u201d with the\nresult that even more stringent anti\nLabor legislation will be approved.\nWhile some express doubt in the\nability of President Truman to ob\ntain a solid backing of Organized\nLabor at the polls, due largely to his\nuse of the injunction to prevent\nstrikes, others argue that the presi\ndent has proven himself a true Roose\nvelt liberal. They contend that he did\neverything in his power to continue\ntire pro-Labor program of the late\nPresident Roosevelt, and that he was\nprevented from doing so only by the\nsolid Republican vote against him,\nplus the votes of the poll-tax Demo\ncrats in the South.\nPresident Truman is credited with\nhaving fought unsuccessfully for\nlaws to prevent price increases; he\nfought for an adequate housing pro\ngram; he battled for FEPC legisla\ntion, and he strove for a reduction in\nincome taxes beneficial to the work\ners instead of to big business. All of\nthese things were advocated by Or\nganized Labor, and the question arises\nas to whether or not another Demo\ncratic nominee for president would en\ndeavor to carry out such a program in\nthe interests of Labor.\nHowever, the question still is un\nanswered as to whether President Tru\nman, in spite of such efforts in the\n\nCourt Verdict\n(Continued from Page One)\nm the act. To the majority, it proved\nthat the sponsors of Taft-Hartley\ndidn't intend to interfere with the\nfreedom of labor\u2019s papers. To the\nminority, Taft\u2019s remarks complicated\nthe meaning of the statute and in\ncreased their conviction that the\nCourt should pass on the basic con\nstitutional question.\nJustice Wiley Rutledge, who wrote\nthe minority opinion, summed up the\nmajority decision this way:\n\u201cCongress did not intend to forbid\nexpenditures from union funds to sus\ntain the publication of the union\u2019s\npolitical views in the regular course\nof publishing and distributing a union\nnewspaper, with distribution limited\nto union members.\"\nThe minority opinion points out that\nlabor\u2019s constitutional rights of free\nspeech, press and assembly are far\nmore extensive than this and that the\nCourt might well have declared this\npart of Taft-Hartley unconstitutional.\nNarrow as it is, however, the deci\nsion is welcomed as the first victory\nin labor\u2019s legal fight against Taft\nHartleyism.\nI President Philip Murray, who was\nindividually indicted along with the\nCIO on the case, said: \u201cThe CIO and\nits president arc naturally gratified\nby this decision of the Supreme Court\nof the U. S. We are pleased that the\nhighest court of our land has sustain\ned the right of labor to enjoy a free\npress.\u201d\nFurther Supreme Court judgment\non the constitutionality of Taft-Hart\nley will not be made until its fall\nterm. Waiting action in a lower court\nnow is an AFL case which raises the\nright of unions to buy radio time and\nnewspaper space to denounce anti-la\nbor laws and their advocates.\nThe court also sidestepped an op\nportunity to rule on the validity of\nTaft-Hartley\u2019s non-Communist affi\ndavits section. It sustained that part\nof a lower court\u2019s ruling in the case\nbrought by the National Maritime Un.\nion-CIO which upheld the require\nment that unions wishing to make use\nof the NLRB must file financial data.\nTherefore, the Court did not \u201cfind it\nnecessary to reach or consider the\nvalidity of Section 9h\u201d\u2014the non-Com\nmunist affidavits section.\nIn an effort to secure the right of\nthe United Steelworkers to bargain\nabout welfare and pension funds, CIO\nCounsel Arthur Goldberg has filed a\nbrief in a federal court to force a\nruling on 9h. Since the union has\nfiled its fiscal statements this ease\nwill force a ruling on the Commun\nist disclaimer section.\npast in the interests of Labor, could\ncommand solid Labor support at the\npolls. Some have gone so far as to\nsay that while the CIO-PAC un.\ndoubtediy would be forced to endorse\nhim for reelection if he is nominated,\nthat he would take such a \u201clicking\u201d\nat the polls that it virtually would be\nthe end of PAC power and prestige.\nOn the other hand, it is being asked:\n\u201cWould Organized Labor be better\noff to throw its support behind a less\nliberal candidate just in order to elect\nhim?\u201d\nAgain the answers are divided.\nLabor leaders believe that they are\nstrong enough politically to elect any\ncandidate for president behind .whom\nthe solid support of the rank and file\nis thrown.\n\u201cBut will the rank and file get\nsolidly behind any one candidate?\u201d\nthey ask.\nThat\u2019s the $64 question.\nSo, as the discussions go on within\nthe ranks of Labor, pro and con, La\nbor leaders are marking time.\nBut while they are saying little for\npublication, they cannot disguise their\ngenuine concern. They know that La\nbor\u2019s future for years to come hangs\nin the balance, and there is little they\ncan do about it, but wait and hope\nuntil after the convention delegates\nhave spoken.\nEmbarrassed\n(Continued from Page One)\nThe catch to this is that an indi\nvidual firm\u2019s success depends on buy\ning at one price and selling at an\nother, in the face of ever-changing\nprices for both products and materials.\nIf an individual concern figured the\nprices of its inventory and all other\ncosts at current market prices instead\nof the prices it actually paid, including\nlabor at prevailing wageB instead of\nthe wages it actually paid labor, then\nit could always show that it was mak\ning no profit.\nAnother argument seen in news\npaper advertisements these days is\nthat profits must be high because\noperating costs are high. This is an\nappeal to the worker\u2019s own experience\nwith the high cost of living. But\nthere is no comparison between the\ntwo. The worker consumes whatever\nhe buys; the corporations sell what\never they buy.\nThe strongest argument in defense\nof high profits and incidentally against\nhigher wages, now being made is that\nthe workers are already getting more\nthan the cost of living would justify.\nBetween 1939 and 1947, according tq\nthis argument, hourly earnings in the\nmanufacturing industries increased\nfrom 63 cents to $1.22, or, on an in\ndex basis, from 100 per cent to 192\nper cent. This argument deals with\nhourly earnings and not with total\nearnings of all employes\u2014$128.1 bil\nlion in 1947, against $47.8 billion in\n1939.\nThe billions acoount not only for the\nincrease in hourly earnings between\n1939 and 1947, but for the increase\nin the number of workers. On the\nbasis of these billions, the workers,\nas already indicated, failed to keep up\nwith the rise in national income, but\nthe corporations ran way ahead of it.\nT\nGOP Chairman\nHas Anti-Labor\nVoting Record\nRepresentative Hugh D. Scott, new\nly appointed chairman of the Repub\nlican National Committee, \u201chas a\nvoting record which shows him to be\nan enemy of labor,\u201d Albert J. Fitz\ngerald, chairman of the National\nLabor Committee for Wallace and\nTaylor said this week.\n\u2018\u201cIf Tom Dewey thinks he\u2019s going\nto give a New Look to the Repub\nlican Party with this appointment\npayoff to the Grundy machine for\nbacking his nomination, he\u2019s sadly\nmistaken,\u201d Fitzgerald declared. \u201cIt\njust increases the exposure of the\nlabor-hating and big-business-loving\ncharacter of the GOP.\u201d\nDescribing Scott as \u201cthe Taft-Hart\nley chairman of a Taft-Hartley\nparty,\u201d he noted that Scott \u201cnot only\nsupported and voted for the Taft\nHartley act all the way through, but\nhis anti-labor record in Congress\nalso dates back as far as 1941.\n\u201cAt that time, Scott voted for the\nSmith anti-labor bill, to destroy the\nWagner Act, restore anti-union in\njunctions, outlaw new union shop con\ntracts and impose heavy penalties on\nunions.\n\u201cScott also voted for the so-called\nportal-to-portal bill to undermine the\nWage-Hour act and weaken its en\nforcement; and to cut Labor Depart\nment appropriations for services to\nthe working people.\n\u201cIn regard to rent control, housing\nand taxation, Scott\u2019s record in Con\ngress is equally anti-labor and pro\nprofiteer.\n\u201cHe voted for the Wolcott bill per\nmitting a IS per cent increase in\nrents. He opposed labor efforts to in\ncrease the number of home loans\navailable to veterans. He voted\nagainst the Forand motion to help\nlow-income persons by increasing\ntheir tax exemptions from $500 to\n$600.\n\u201cScott\u2019s Congressional services to\nthe rich and to big-business monop\nolists are as noteworthy as his dis\nservices to labor.\n\u201cHe was one of several Congress\nmen who sponsored a community\nproperty tax clause, to benefit large\ntaxpayers. He supported the Bul\nwinkle bill, which exempts railroads\nfrom anti-trust legislation. He sup\nported the Rizley bill to enable na\ntural gas producers to obtain a wind\nfall through exemption from rate-con\ntrol by the Federal Power Commis\nsion.\u201d\nPlant Accident\nRate Is High\nWith Ohio\u2019s industrial accident rec\nord remaining bleak, figures released\nthis week by the U. S. Department of\nLabor offer a startling comparison.\nLast year, 17,000 American indus\ntrial workers were killed on the job\u2014\na shocking commentary on the'lack of\nsafety measures in plants.\nBut more than 1000 of those who\ndied in job accidents were killed in\nOhio. This figure shows Ohio must\nbe high on the nation\u2019s death list.\nActing Secretary of Labor John W.\nGibson says that America has over\ntwo million job injuries every year\u2014\none injury every 10 seconds. This is\na financial loss of three and a half\nbillion dollars a year, he pointed out.\nPlan Test of Non-Communfst\nAffidavit T-H Provisions\n(Continued from Page One) j\naccord with the First amendment to\nthe Constitution.\n\u201cIt abridges the freedom of speech\nand the right of assembly without a\nshowing of clear and present danger,\u201d\nhe said in reference to the law.\nCounsel for Local 66 sought with\nout success to secure a temporary\norder from Supreme Court Justice\nJackson ordering the election be post\nponed pending final decision in the\ncase.\nThe steel union attack on Taft-\u25a0\nHartley. affidavits arose from the In\nland Steel Co. case. In April the\nNLRB ordered the Indiana steel firm\nto bargain with the USA-CIO over\npensions\u2014provided the union filed af\nfidavits within 30 days.\nThe union is asking the circuit court\nto set aside that proviso in the NLRB\norder, on grounds that the affidavits\nare contrary to Constitutional rights.\nThe section of T-H requiring affi\ndavits \u201cgoes further than any previ\nous statutory attempt to suppress the\nfreedoms granted by the First Amend\nment,\u201d the union brief charged, and\nis an attempt to restrict free\ndom of belief.\u201d\nLanguage of the affidavit is vague\nexcept as it applies to \u201cmembers of\nthe Communist Party,\u201d the brief said,\nand the wording does \u201cnot give notice\nof exactly what are the prescribed be\nliefs or activities\nRecalling that CIO has often been\nwrongfully smeared as Communist or\nCommunist-controlled, the steel union\nbrief argued that the vagueness of the\naffidavit might lead to prosecution of\nunion leaders. Taking exception to\nHelp To PAC\n(Continued from Page One)\nout of every 100 are turned down.\nRevealing the basic infamy of the\nOhio law\u2014which carries no humane\ndefinition of \u201csuitable work\u201d\u2014is this\nfact: The Ohio disqualification rate,\nwhich was down to 15.1 in the first\nthree months of 1947, had climbed to\nits present level of 24.4, by the end of\nthe year\u2014the latest period for which\nfigures were available.\nIn some cases, disqualification re\nsults from actions of the Bureau of\nUnemployment Compensation person\nnel, who deliberately seek to keep\nthe case load down. But in the ma\njority of the cases, the blame falls\nsquarely on the law itself.\n\u201cThis is a -most important prob\nlem,\u201d Kroll said, \u201cand it will grow in\nimportance when this country suffers\na recession. Under the present setup,\nany business recession would mean\nthat the entire economy of our state\nwould be upset.\n\u201cUnemployment compensation was j\nmeant to be a \u2018cushion\u2019 for our ecou- I\nomy in bad times. The way the law\nis now drawn up, our workers would j\nfind no cushion when the bottom'\ndrops out from under. Instead the\nworker would, find just plain hard\nrock.\n\u201cUntil we get a liberal Legislature\nand state administration in Ohio, we\nwill continue to have these outrage\nous statistics.\n\u201cEvery Ohio worker has a definite\nstake in the Ohio CIO\u2019s battle for a\nhumane, decent, understanding Unem\nployment Compensation law. There\nfore every worker should join whole\nheartedly in the Ohio CIO-PAC\u2019s fight\nin 1948.\u201d\nGrab \u2019em up at a Big Savings!\nPANTS SPECIALS\nat Carlton\u2019s Tomorrow\nas low as\nGabardines, Tropicals, Shark\nskins', Bedford Cords and .other\npopular fabrics\u2014priced to save\nyou PLENTY at Carlton\u2019s.\nEvery pair is custom touch\ntailored for comfort and good\nlooking fit by Carlton\u2019s expert\ncraftsmen.\n\"Charge It\"\nF>; wmU| or twko\nmonthly at no extra\nsort at Carlton** t\nthe vague language of the law, the\nbrief asked;\n\u201cOf what avail is it to Philip\nMurray to know in his heart that he\nis a patriotic American, that his activi\nties and affiliations have in no way\nfurthered the overthrow of govern\nment, and that his every effort has\nbeen devoted to the preservation and\nextension of progressive democratic\ninstitutions?\"\nUnion Group Quits\nAmerican Legion\nThe National Conference of Union\nLabor Legionnaires has withdrawn\nfrom the American Legion and has\nestablished a new organization of\nunion labor veterans which plans \u201cto\nfight against the undemocratic activi\nties of the American Legion.\u201d\nThe conference, composed of trade\nunion members Of the Legion was\nformed in 1938. Its pwpose was \u201cto\nestablish within the American Legion\ndemocratic principles beneficial to the\nrank and file veterans of organized\nlabor.\u201d\nIt was announced that the confer\nence which held its 10th annual con\nvention at Chicago, that the group\u2019s\nactivities had created a demand\n\u201cfrom other veterans\u2019 organizations,\nunaffiliated veterans of organized la\nbor and from organized labor\u201d for a\nbroadening of its membership.\nBecause the Legion has continued\nto discriminate against organized la\nbor by refusing to charter trade union\nposts, the conference unanimously\nadopted a resolution to include any\nperson sympathetic to organized labor\nwho served in the United States forces\nor with any of the allies of the United\nStates during time of war and was\ndischarged honorably.\nThe group changed its'name to the\nNational Conference of Union Labor\nat the same meeting. Richard Reis\ninger, Cleveland, Ohio, regional Auto\nWorkers director, is chairman of the\nre-organization committee.\nSpeakers at the conference included\nMeyer Bernstein, CIO veterans rep\nresentative and Eugene Cotton, CIO\nPackinghouse Workers counsel. Both\npointed out how the T-H law operates\nagainst labor.\nThe conference passed resolutions\nurging repeal of the T-H law, defeat\nof the Mundt-Nixon bill and passage\nof the Taft-Ellender-Wagner bill.\nAhearn To Head\nSafety Meet\nPresident Truman has appointed\nVincent P. Ahearn as executiveVfac\ntor for the President\u2019s Conference on\nIndustrial Safety to tie held in. Wash\nington, September 27-28-29. The\nPresident asked the Department. of\nLabor to call the Conference through\nits Bureau of Labor Standards, \u201ci*\nAcceptance of the executive'direc\ntorship by Ahearn marked one of the\nmajor developments in the swiftenoV\ning plans to-develop a natipn-wide\nprogram to reduce the human and,eco\nnomic losses caused by. work injuries\nand deaths.\nWorking with William L. Connolly,\nDirector of the Bareau of' Labor\u201e\nStandards, Ahearn will seek the co\noperation of representatives of. labor,\nmanagement, and other interested\ngroups in selecting necessary commit\ntees and other key officers, and pre\nparing the agenda for the Confer\nence.\nSince 1926 Ahearn has been, execu\ntive secretary of the National Sand\nand Gravel Association and was ;an in\ndustry member of the Nationajj War\nLabor Board; industry member Of the\nLabor-Management Advisory. Commit\ntee to the Director of the United\nStates Conciliation Service, Depart\nment of Labor; and alternate manage,\nment delegates, President\u2019s Labor\nManagement Conference.\nAlso he was president of, Amer\nican Trade Association Execptiyesj'\n1942-43; 'president of 'WasUiigteta\nTrade Association Executives, 1942\n43; and chairman, ManufactUripJf.\nTrade Group National Industrial Con\nference, 1941.\n\u201cBecause of his leadership, fxe4a-\ntive and organising ability, and ex\ntensive experience in the field :of la\nbor-management cooperation, Mr.\nAhearn\u2019s willingness to take op this\nvital job assures the success St the\nConference,\u201d Acting Secretary, of La\nbor John W. Gibson said. ,1\nSSA Office Hours\nChange Announced\nThe office hours of the SOCipl Se\ncurity Administration, -dtp First Na\ntional Tower, now-are 8:30 A. $d* to\n4:45 P.M. X.:\ni Richard H. Hendrick, local: man\nager, stated that the change in. houri\nis being effected in order to/ay4jld the\nnew closing hours for dtfWhtown\nstores and the resulting increased de\nmand for bus transportation ai 6:00\no\u2019clock. r .'\u2019'\u25a0\u25a0o- V- f\u00ab n.j\nYou may call it a \"light\u201d bill, but lighting'* only a\npart of it. Actually, it'* a monthly pay roll for\u2019' the\nmany electric helper* that make life easier for you.\nHave you ever wondered what these helper* cost\nyou to run? Here's a little test to see how good V\nguesspr you are. Put down what you think it costs\nyou to run each electric appliance for one day. _\n3SW\n\nMmMm\nWater Heater\nU\u00ab\u00bbs\nToaster\nha ea* \u25a0*_\nDishwasher\nMaahat aed Haetiay Pati\nSTVlS'i\nAdd this dally fatal and multiply by SO for year monthly total.\n\u2014!-1\u2014 -a day a SO day* S_'\nThit\u2019i wur guess. Compare it with your monthly clectrie\nbill. Most people overestimate. That's because elto\ntricity does so much for so little! You're right. It'* fc\nvery light bill!\nOHIO\nCOMPANY","height":"26108","width":"20564"}}
